>based Pompeii
I believe that you need to know two of three things to write a story: the beginning, the end, and the key moment in the middle.
You can start with one, but that has to be with the sole purpose of figuring out one of the two missing parts.
What I'm about to say next will trigger someone. If you dawdle around, you'll have a weak opening, no idea where to end, and call your plot a slow-burn.
A proper slow-burn has a definite plot, in fact, layers of it that rely on the initial opening to be strong and hold the reader. If the layers that follow degenerate into something that look like an aimless slice-of-life or the characters never seem to change as a result of their actions and the following consequences, it's pantsing your ass off and then forgetting that you need an ass to do an asspull later on. This also affects way to many TV series that try too hard to give the viewers continual twists. Sooner or later, it makes dick-all sense.
Also see: soap opera.
